]''\n| Lieutenant Jake LaRussa\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Pawn (film)|Pawn]]''\n| Charlie\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''The Gettysburg Story''\n| Himself/Narrator\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Pioneer (film)|Pioneer]]''\n| Ferris\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[The Monkey's Paw (2013 film)|The Monkey's Paw]]''\n| Tony Cobb\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''{{sortname|The|Girl on the Train|The Girl on the Train (2013 film)}}''\n| Det. Lloyd Martin\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[The Nut Job]]''\n| King\n| Voice\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[In the Blood (2014 film)|In the Blood]]''\n| Casey\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Jarhead 2: Field of Fire]]''\n| Major James Gavins\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[A Good Marriage (film)|A Good Marriage]]''\n| Holt Ramsey\n|\n|-\n|  2014\n| ''[[Gutshot Straight]]''\n| Duffy\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[23 Blast]]''\n| Coach Farris\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Exeter (film)|Exeter]]''\n| Father Conway\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Band of Robbers]]''\n| Injun Joe\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Gridlocked (2015 film)|Gridlocked]]''\n| Korver\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Beyond Glory: Tour of Duty''\n| Himself\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Isolation''\n| William \n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Don't Breathe]]''\n| Norman Nordstrom (The Blind Man)\n| [[Fangoria]] Chainsaw Award for Best Supporting Actor<ref>{{cite web|title=Never mind Oscar, here's the 2017 FANGORIA Chainsaw Awards Nominees Ballot!|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/never-mind-oscar-heres-the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-nominees-ballot/|website=FANGORIA\u00ae|accessdate=14 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806233824/http://fangoria.com/new/never-mind-oscar-heres-the-2017-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-nominees-ballot/|archive-date=2017-08-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Beyond Valkyrie: Dawn of the 4th Reich]]''\n| [[Major General]] [[Emil F. Reinhardt]]\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Hostiles (film)|Hostiles]]''\n| Colonel Abraham Biggs\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Justice''\n| Mayor Pierce\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Braven]]''\n| Linden Braven\n| Supporting role\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Mortal Engines (film)|Mortal Engines]]''\n| Shrike\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Gandhi Murder]]''\n|  Sunil Raina \n|\n|-\n|2019\n| ''VFW''\n| Fred Parras \n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Rogue Warfare''\n| President\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Rogue Warfare 2: The Hunt''\n| President\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''Rogue Warfare: Death of a Nation''\n| President\n|\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Avatar 2]]''\n| Colonel Miles Quaritch<ref name=\"Main Vilain\">{{cite news|author=Max Evry|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/877415-colonel-quaritch-will-be-the-main-villain-in-the-avatar-sequels#/slide/1|title= Colonel Quaritch Will be the Main Villain in the Avatar Sequels | publisher=[[CraveOnline|ComingSoon.net]] |date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=September 30, 2017|}}</ref>\n| ''Post-production''\n|-\n| 2023\n| ''[[Avatar 3]]''\n| Colonel Miles Quaritch<ref name=\"Main Vilain\" />\n| ''Post-production''\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|   1985\n| ''[[Death of a Salesman (1985 film)|Death of a Salesman]]''  \n| Happy\n| TV movie\n|-\n|  1986\u20131988\n| ''[[Crime Story (U.S. TV series)|Crime Story]]''\n| Attorney David Abrams\n| 26 episodes\n|-\n|  1989\n|  ''[[The Equalizer]]''\n| Joseph Morrison\n| Episode: \"Lullaby of Darkness\"\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Babe Ruth (film)|Babe Ruth]]''  \n| [[Babe Ruth]]\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Taking Back My Life: The Nancy Ziegenmeyer Story]]''  \n| Steven Ziegenmeyer \n| TV movie\n|-\n|   1994\n| ''[[Baseball (TV series)|Baseball]]''\n| Various voices \n| Documentary miniseries by [[Ken Burns]]\n|-\n|  1995\n| ''[[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air]]''\n| Criminal Gun Shooter\n| Episode: \"Bullets Over Bel-Air\"\n|-\n|   1996\n| ''The West''\n| Various voices \n| Documentary miniseries by [[Ken Burns]]\n|-\n|  1997\n| ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]''\n| Dr. James Houghton\n| Episode: \"[[New Lease (The Outer Limits)|New Lease]]\"\n|-\n|  1997\n| ''[[Liberty! The American Revolution]]''\n| [[George Washington]]\n| Voice; 6 episodes\n|-\n|   1998\n| ''[[Escape: Human Cargo]]''\n| Dennis McNatt \n| TV movie produced by [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].\n|-\n|   2000\n| ''[[Running Mates (2000 film)|Running Mates]]''\n| Ron Noble (Financier)\n| Uncredited; TV movie shown on the [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT Network]].\n|-\n|  2000\u20132001\n| ''[[The Fugitive (2000 TV series)|The Fugitive]]''\n| Ben Charnquist\n| 5 episodes\n|-\n|  2001\n| ''[[After the Storm (2001 film)|After the Storm]]''\n| Sergeant Major Jim\n| TV movie\n|-\n|  2002\n| ''[[Ed (TV series)|Ed]]''\n| Jack Foster\n| Episode: \"Wheel of Justice\"\n|-\n|  2003\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Michael Baxter\n| Episode: \"Escape\"\n|-\n|  2005\n| ''[[Jonny Zero]]''\n| Officer Tanner\n| Episode: \"To Serve and to Protect\"\n|-\n|  2005\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Terry Dorn\n| Episode: \"New York Minute\"\n|-\n|  2007\n| ''[[The Bronx Is Burning]]''\n| Inspector Dowd\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n|   2008\n| ''Medal of Honor''\n| Narrator\n| [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] documentary\n|-\n|  2009\n| ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]''\n| Axel Kaspers\n| Episode: \"Revolution\"\n|-\n|  2009\n| ''[[Psych]]''\n| Mr. Salamatchla\n| Episode: \"Shawn Gets the Yips\"\n|-\n|  2011\n| ''[[Terra Nova (TV series)|Terra Nova]]''\n| Commander Nathaniel Taylor\n| 13 episodes Lead Role\n|- \n|  2012\n| ''[[In Plain Sight]]''\n| James Wiley Shannon\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n|  2014\u20132015\n| ''[[Salem (TV series)|Salem]]''\n| [[Increase Mather]]\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n|  2015\n| ''To Appomattox''   \n| [[John Brown (abolitionist)|John Brown]]\n| Upcoming series\n|-\n|  2015\u20132019\n| ''[[Into the Badlands (TV series)|Into the Badlands]]''\n| Waldo\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n|2019\n|[[The Rookie (TV series)|''The Rookie'']]\n|Chief Williams\n|Episode: \"The Checklist\"\n|}\n\n===Web===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|  2018\n| ''[[Uncharted Live Action Fan Film]]''\n| Victor \"Sully\" Sullivan\n| Fan Film\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Call of Duty: Ghosts]]''\n| Elias Walker<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charlieintel.com/2013/10/01/brandon-j-routh-and-stephen-lang-confirmed-as-one-of-voice-actors-for-ghosts/|title=Brandon J. Routh and Stephen Lang confirmed as one of voice actors for Ghosts|work=Charlie INTEL|access-date=2013-10-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220301/http://www.charlieintel.com/2013/10/01/brandon-j-routh-and-stephen-lang-confirmed-as-one-of-voice-actors-for-ghosts/|archive-date=2013-10-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| \n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size: 95%\"\n|-\n! width=\"25%\"|Award\n! width=\"25%\"|Category\n! width=\"5%\"|Result\n|- bgcolor=CCCFFF\n| colspan=4 align=center| '''''Gods and Generals''''' (2003)\n|-\n| Grace Award || Acting || {{Won}}\n|-\n|- bgcolor=CCCFFF\n| colspan=4 align=center| '''''Avatar''''' (2009)\n|-\n| rowspan=2| MTV Movie Award || Best Fight <small>(with [[Sam Worthington]])</small> || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Villain || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Saturn Award || Best Supporting Actor || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| Teen Choice Award || Choice Movie: Fight <small>(with Sam Worthington)</small> || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Villain || {{Nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Stephen Lang (actor)}}\n* {{IMDb name|2332|Stephen Lang}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://lortel.org/Archives/CreditableEntity/6467 Stephen Lang] at [[Internet Off-Broadway Database]]\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/stephan-lang-larry-smith-beyond-glory/ Interview] on ''Beyond Glory'' at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]]\n* {{C-SPAN|Stephen Lang}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n| title = Artistic Director of the [[Actors Studio]]\n| years = 2004\u20132006\n| with = [[Carlin Glynn]]<br>and [[Lee Grant]]\n| before = [[Estelle Parsons]]<br>Vacant (2003\u20132004)\n| after = [[Carlin Glynn]]<br>[[Lee Grant]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lang, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Hungarian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swarthmore College alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:George School alumni]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Stephen Lang\n| image = Stephen Lang 2014.jpg\n| caption = Lang in February 2014\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|7|11}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| education = [[George School]]\n| alma mater = [[Swarthmore College]]\n| occupation = Actor, playwright\n| yearsactive = 1981\u2013present\n| children = 4\n| parents = [[Eugene Lang]]<br/>Theresa Volmer\n| relatives = [[Jane Lang]] (sister)\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Lang''' (born July 11, 1952) is an American screen and stage actor, and playwright. He is known for roles in films including ''[[Manhunter (film)|Manhunter]]'' (1986), ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]]'', ''[[Tombstone (film)|Tombstone]]'' (both 1993), ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]'' (2003), ''[[Public Enemies (2009 film)|Public Enemies]]'' (2009) and ''[[Don't Breathe]]'' (2016). He received a [[Tony Award]] nomination for his role in the 1992 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of ''[[The Speed of Darkness (play)|The Speed of Darkness]]'' and won the [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance in [[James Cameron]]'s ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' (2009). From 2004 to 2006, he was co-[[artistic director]] of the [[Actors Studio]].\n\n==Personal life==\nLang was born in [[New York City]], the youngest child of Theresa ([[married and maiden names|n\u00e9e]] Volmar, d. 2008) and [[Eugene Lang]] (1919\u20132017), a prominent entrepreneur and philanthropist.<ref name=\"filmr\">{{cite web |url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/63/Stephen-Lang.html |title=Stephen Lang Biography (1952-) |publisher=Filmreference.com |accessdate=2010-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100204234156/http://www.filmreference.com/film/63/Stephen-Lang.html |archive-date=2010-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref> Lang's mother was a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] of [[German Americans|German]] and [[Irish Americans|Irish]] descent, while his father was [[Jews|Jewish]]. Lang's paternal grandparents were Jewish emigrants from [[Hungarian Jews|Hungary]] and [[Russian Jews|Russia]].<ref name=people>{{cite magazine |last=Stark |first=John |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20117770,00.html |title=Forgoing His Father's Millions, Stephen Lang Bootstraps to Acting Fame with the Help of a Few Good Men. ''Vol. 33. \u2116 21.'' |magazine=People.com |date=1990-05-28 |accessdate=2010-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100326144606/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20117770,00.html |archive-date=2010-03-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Panarello | first = Joseph | title = The Multiple Personalities of Stephen Lang | publisher = broadwayworld.com | url = http://www.broadwayworld.com/printcolumn.cfm?id=20371 | accessdate = 2009-08-12 | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6GbigYKJS?url=http://broadwayworld.com/printcolumn.php?id=20371 | archive-date = 2013-05-14 | url-status = live }}</ref> He has two elder siblings\u2014[[Jane Lang|Jane]], an attorney and activist, and David, who served as an executive at REFAC, the company their father founded in 1952.<ref name=\"people\"/> Lang's father donated much of his net worth (in excess of $150 million) to charity and did not leave an inheritance to his children, believing they each needed to learn to become self-sufficient.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/2006-07-25-heirs-usat_x.htm | work=USA Today | first1=Rachel | last1=Breitman | first2=Del | last2=Jones | title=Heirs not-so-apparent? | date=2006-07-26 | access-date=2017-09-15 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625211512/http://www.usatoday.com/money/2006-07-25-heirs-usat_x.htm | archive-date=2012-06-25 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLang attended elementary school in [[Jamaica Estates, Queens]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023697/bio |title=Stephen Lang Biography - Yahoo! Movies |publisher=Movies.yahoo.com |date=1952-07-11 |accessdate=2010-05-30|archive-date=13 October 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013123624/http://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800023697/bio}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9401E5DA173CF93AA25757C0A96E958260 | work=The New York Times | title=Stephen Lang, 'An Actor's Actor' | first=Alvin | last=Klein | date=1998-04-19 | accessdate=2010-04-03}}{{Failed verification|date=December 2014}}</ref> His middle school was a New York City public school, George Ryan Junior High School, in nearby Fresh Meadows.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Orion 1966 - Junior High School 216 Yearbook|last=|first=|publisher=Faculty Press Inc., 1449 37th Street  Brooklyn, NY 11218|year=1966|isbn=|location=Yearbook - distributed to graduates.|pages=48}}</ref> For high school, he attended [[George School]], a Quaker boarding school in Newtown, PA and graduated from there a year early (1969). He graduated from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1973 with a degree in English Literature; on May 30, 2010, Swarthmore awarded him an honorary degree in recognition of his distinguished career in theatre, television, and film.<ref name=swarthmore>Attendee of the ceremony for his son Sergio's graduation, Ricardo V Rivas, EA, president of the Texas Society of Enrolled Agents and http://www.swarthmore.edu/x28750.xml {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100408144812/http://www.swarthmore.edu/x28750.xml |date=2010-04-08 }}</ref> His youngest son, Noah, received his bachelor's degree during the same ceremony.<ref name=swarthmore/> He also holds an Honorary Doctorate in Humane Letters from [[Jacksonville University]] and was an artist in residence at [[Northeastern University]] in 2011.<ref>[http://www.northeastern.edu/humanities/events-and-programs/archived-center-events/fall-2010-spring-2011/artists-and-practitioners-in-residence-program/stephen-lang/ Stephen Lang<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205030619/http://www.northeastern.edu/humanities/events-and-programs/archived-center-events/fall-2010-spring-2011/artists-and-practitioners-in-residence-program/stephen-lang/ |date=2012-12-05 }}</ref> In the fall of 2015, Lang served as a Jury Member for the [[Woodstock Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.woodstockfilmfestival.com/awards2015.php|title=Woodstock Film Festival - 2014 MAVERICK Awards|access-date=2016-01-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113065641/http://www.woodstockfilmfestival.com/awards2015.php|archive-date=2016-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Stephen Lang and Senator Daniel Inouye (Hawaii).jpg|thumb|right|Lang (left) with [[Daniel Inouye|Senator Daniel Inouye]] in 2005|alt=Lang with Senator Daniel Inouye]]\nLang played Harold (Happy) Loman in the 1984 Broadway revival of ''[[Death of a Salesman (1985 film)|Death of a Salesman]]'' and the 1985 television film with [[Dustin Hoffman]] as [[Willy Loman]], and appeared in the first [[Hannibal Lecter]] film ''[[Manhunter (film)|Manhunter]]'' (1986), as reporter [[Freddy Lounds]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://search.msn.com/images/results.aspx?q=STEPHEN+LANG&FORM=MSNH&mkt=en- |title=STEPHEN LANG - Bing Afbeeldingen |publisher=Search.msn.com |date= |accessdate=2010-05-30 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He played attorney David Abrams in the television series ''[[Crime Story (U.S. TV series)|Crime Story]]'' (1986\u201388). He played the title role in the NBC movie ''Babe Ruth'' (1991). He later played the \"One Armed Man\" in the 2000 revival of ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]'' starring Tim Daly. The series was a modest success but lasted only one season because of its large production budget.\n\nIn 1992, he was nominated for a [[Tony Award]] for his lead role in ''[[The Speed of Darkness (play)|The Speed of Darkness]].'' His film role in [[Last Exit to Brooklyn (film)|''Last Exit to Brooklyn'']] (1989) garnered him widespread critical acclaim, but its limited release prevented the film from reaching a wider audience. On stage, he was the first to play the role of Colonel Nathan Jessup in ''[[A Few Good Men (play)|A Few Good Men]],'' a role made famous on film (1992) by [[Jack Nicholson]]. He is the winner of over half a dozen theatre awards including the Drama Desk and Helen Hayes awards.\n\nIn films, he played [[George Pickett|Maj. Gen. George E. Pickett]] in ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]]'' (1993) and the lead role of [[Stonewall Jackson|Thomas \"Stonewall\" Jackson]] in the Gettysburg [[prequel]] ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]'' (2003), both from director [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]. He considers ''Gods and Generals'' to be his finest performance. Arguably, his most famous film role, before ''Avatar'', was his portrayal of the villainous [[Ike Clanton]] in the successful [[Western (genre)|Western]] ''[[Tombstone (film)|Tombstone]]'' (1993) with [[Kurt Russell]] and [[Val Kilmer]].\n\nShortly before [[Arthur Miller]]'s death in February 2005, Lang appeared in his long-time friend's last play, titled ''Finishing the Picture''. It premiered in 2004 at [[Chicago]]'s [[Goodman Theatre]], where Lang had the second run of his own play, ''Beyond Glory,'' which had premiered in Arlington, Virginia, early in 2004, and his Tony-nominated portrayal for ''The Speed of Darkness.'' Lang also performed ''Beyond Glory'', a one-man show, for troops deployed overseas.<ref name=parade>{{cite news | title = In Step With: Stephen Lang | publisher = Parade Magazine | date = June 5, 2005 | url =https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=20050603&id=TGFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VQQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4628,698899}}</ref> In 2006, he played the role of Colonel Littlefield in [[John Patrick Shanley]]'s play ''[[Defiance (play)|Defiance]]''. He brought ''Beyond Glory'' to Roundabout's Off-Broadway Laura Pels Theatre in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |author=Daniel Henninger |url=http://www.opinionjournal.com/columnists/dhenninger/?id=110010444 |title=Wonder Land - WSJ.com |publisher=Opinionjournal.com |date=2007-08-09 |accessdate=2010-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522175237/http://www.opinionjournal.com/columnists/dhenninger/?id=110010444 |archive-date=2010-05-22 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since its New York City premiere, ''Beyond Glory'' has been nominated for a Drama Desk Award and a Lucille Lortel Award both for outstanding solo performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/arts/2008/04/28/2008-04-28_drama_desk_nominees_announced.html?page=1 |title=Drama Desk nominees announced |publisher=Nydailynews.com |date=2008-04-28 |accessdate=2010-05-30 | location=New York | first=Joe | last=Dziemianowicz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Lucille Lortel Awards |author2=Lucille Lortel Foundation |author3=Off-Broadway database |url=http://www.lortel.org/LLF_awards/index.cfm?page=nominees |title=Lucille Lortel Awards, Off-Broadway Awards |publisher=Lortel.org |accessdate=2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206082535/http://www.lortel.org/LLF_awards/index.cfm?page=nominees |archivedate=February 6, 2010 }}</ref> A movie about the play has been produced and released.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNary |first1=Dave |title=Stephen Lang's Medal of Honor Movie 'Beyond Glory' Picked Up by Gravitas |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/stephen-lang-beyond-glory-tribute-movie-gravitas-1201773278/ |website=Variety Magazine |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLang has a role in the ESPN miniseries ''[[The Bronx Is Burning]]'', as well as roles in independent features ''Save Me'' and ''From Mexico with Love''. He plays a lead role in [[James Cameron]]'s sci-fi epic ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' as the villainous Colonel Quaritch.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969650.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 | work=Variety | title=Lang, Rodriguez armed for 'Avatar' | first=Anne | last=Thompson | date=2007-08-02 | access-date=2007-08-03 | archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/68FxdlG6s?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117969650?refCatId=13 | archive-date=2012-06-08 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Stephen Lang by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|left|Lang at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] in San Diego, California, promoting ''Terra Nova''.]]\nIn 2009, he appeared in Michael Mann's film ''[[Public Enemies (2009 film)|Public Enemies]]'' as FBI Agent Charles Winstead,<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983380.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |title=Crudup to play Hoover in 'Public' - Entertainment News, Film News, Media |magazine=Variety |date=2008-04-02 |accessdate=2010-05-30 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090523103842/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117983380.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |archive-date=2009-05-23 |url-status=live }}</ref> the man widely considered to have fired the shots that killed [[John Dillinger]]<ref>{{cite news|first=Kent |last=Biffle |date=6 August 2005 |title=Who drilled Dillinger? Credit goes to Texan |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/fea/texasliving/columnists/all/stories/0807dnlivbiffle.229d4704.html |work=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |accessdate=15 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090712045752/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/fea/texasliving/columnists/all/stories/0807dnlivbiffle.229d4704.html |archivedate=July 12, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9E1t-2ER7QcC&pg=RA3-PA401&lpg=RA3-PA401&dq=charles+winstead+killed+john+dillinger&source=web&ots=gUN80kRurS&sig=4lIUgg3Qcanpn6edSOqXDzP_DXw&hl=en |title=John Dillinger: The Life and Death ... - Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=1933-05-22 |accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref> and in Grant Heslov's ''[[The Men Who Stare at Goats (film)|The Men Who Stare at Goats]]'' alongside [[Jeff Bridges]], [[Kevin Spacey]], [[Ewan McGregor]], and [[George Clooney]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kit |first=Borys |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i39aca7c440d50caa4674abf14f47d382 |title=Rebecca Mader joins 'Goats' herd |publisher=Hollywoodreporter.com |date=2008-10-10 |accessdate=2010-05-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013010218/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/content_display/film/news/e3i39aca7c440d50caa4674abf14f47d382 |archivedate=October 13, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2009, he narrated the [[audiobook]] ''[[Road Rage (audiobook)|Road Rage]]''\u2014which combines the short stories \"[[Duel (1971 film)|Duel]]\" by [[Richard Matheson]] and \"Throttle\" by [[Stephen King]] and [[Joe Hill (writer)|Joe Hill]]\u2014and guest-starred in the ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' season 8 finale, \"[[Revolution (Law & Order: Criminal Intent)|Revolution]]\" in the role of Axel Kaspers. In 2010 he performed the narration for \"The Gettysburg Story: Battlefield Auto Tour,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://GettysburgStory.com|title=Home - The Gettysburg Story|work=The Gettysburg Story}}</ref> the top-selling audio tour of the [[Gettysburg Battlefield]] at [[Gettysburg National Military Park]] in [[Gettysburg, Pennsylvania|Gettysburg]], [[Pennsylvania]]. Written and produced by filmmaker [[Jake Boritt]] and based on works by historian [[Gabor Boritt]] it tells the story of the [[Battle of Gettysburg]] and [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s [[Gettysburg Address]] in [[Gettysburg National Cemetery]]. Lang is also the narrator of the companion [[Public broadcasting|public television]] documentary ''The Gettysburg Story'' presented by [[Maryland Public Television]].\n\nLang played the villain Khalar Zym in the 2011 ''[[Conan the Barbarian (2011 film)|Conan the Barbarian]]'' reboot starring Jason Momoa.<ref>Frappier, Rob. [https://screenrant.com/conan-remake-stephen-lang-robf-66617/ \"Stephen Lang Talks 'Conan' Remake\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101008013117/http://screenrant.com/conan-remake-stephen-lang-robf-66617/ |date=2010-10-08 }} Screen Rant; June 29, 2010</ref> He also played one of the leads, Nathaniel Taylor, in the [[Steven Spielberg]]-produced<ref>Sweney, Mark. [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/18/steven-spielberg-terra-nova-simon-cowell-american-idol \"Fox unveils Steven Spielberg's Terra Nova as it hunts for new Simon Cowell\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161201235941/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/may/18/steven-spielberg-terra-nova-simon-cowell-american-idol |date=2016-12-01 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''; May 18, 2010</ref> TV series ''[[Terra Nova (TV series)|Terra Nova]]''.<ref>Rice, Lynette. [http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/09/14/stephen-lang-in-talks-to-join-foxs-terra-nova/ \"Stephen Lang joins Fox's 'Terra Nova'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100918035918/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2010/09/14/stephen-lang-in-talks-to-join-foxs-terra-nova/ |date=2010-09-18 }} ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''; September 14, 2010</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, he signed on to play Mary Shannon's estranged father in a three episode arc on the final season of the [[USA (TV network)|USA]] television series ''[[In Plain Sight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2012/02/stephen-lang-cast-as-marys-father-on-in-plain-sight|title=Stephen Lang Cast as Mary's Father on In Plain Sight|author=Hmybrd|work=TV Fanatic|access-date=2012-02-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211095743/http://www.tvfanatic.com/2012/02/stephen-lang-cast-as-marys-father-on-in-plain-sight/|archive-date=2012-02-11|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Lang appeared in ''[[The Monkey's Paw (2013 film)|The Monkey's Paw]]'' for [[Chiller TV]].\n\nLang has been confirmed as reprising his role as Colonel Miles Quaritch in the upcoming sequels to ''Avatar''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/10/james-cameron-has-found-avatars-darth-vader-its-stephen-lang/ |title=James Cameron Books Stephen Lang For Next 3 Avatar Films - Deadline |author=Mike Fleming Jr |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=2013-10-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131026090002/http://www.deadline.com/2013/10/james-cameron-has-found-avatars-darth-vader-its-stephen-lang/ |archive-date=2013-10-26 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe plays [[Increase Mather]], in a recurring role, on [[WGN America]]'s first original scripted series, ''[[Salem (TV series)|Salem]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/04/stephen-lang-wgn-america-salem-witch/|title=Stephen Lang Joins WGN America's 'Salem'|author=The Deadline Team|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=2014-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502041636/http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/stephen-lang-wgn-america-salem-witch/|archive-date=2014-05-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLang is part of the cast of [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]'s martial-arts drama ''[[Into the Badlands (TV series)|Into the Badlands]]'', and played The Blind Man in [[Fede Alvarez]]'s hit horror-thriller ''[[Don't Breathe]]'' (2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/stephen-lang-jane-levy-join-802990|title=Stephen Lang, Jane Levy Join Fede Alvarez's Thriller (Exclusive)|author=Rebecca Ford|date=18 June 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2015-06-29|archive-url=https://archive.today/20151113202528/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/stephen-lang-jane-levy-join-802990|archive-date=2015-11-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/avatars-stephen-lang-joins-amcs-into-the-badlands-returns-to-salem-exclusive/|title='Avatar's' Stephen Lang Joins AMC's 'Into the Badlands,' Returns to 'Salem' (Exclusive)|author=Jeff Sneider|date=12 May 2015|work=TheWrap|access-date=2015-06-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150715025340/http://www.thewrap.com/avatars-stephen-lang-joins-amcs-into-the-badlands-returns-to-salem-exclusive/|archive-date=2015-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, Lang lobbied for the role [[Cable (comics)|Cable]] in ''[[Deadpool 2]]'' through captioned [[Twitter]] pictures.<ref>{{cite web |author=Michael Martin |date=February 14, 2016 |url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2016/02/14/deadpool-2-avatars-stephen-lang-lobbies-for-cable-role |title=Deadpool 2: Avatar's Stephen Lang Lobbies for Cable Role |website=[[IGN]] |access-date=August 28, 2016}}</ref> The role ultimately went to [[Josh Brolin]].\n\nIn 2017, he played Colonel Abraham Biggs in ''[[Hostiles (film)|Hostiles]]'', from director [[Scott Cooper (director)|Scott Cooper]]. In 2018, he appeared as father of Joe Braven ([[Jason Momoa]]), Linden Braven in the action thriller film ''[[Braven]]'', and played Shrike in ''[[Mortal Engines (film)|Mortal Engines]]'', which [[Peter Jackson]] produced for [[Universal Pictures]] and Media Rights Capital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-lang-jihae-join-peter-jacksons-mortal-engines-983628|title=Stephen Lang, Jihae, Newcomer Leila George Join Peter Jackson's 'Mortal Engines' (Exclusive)|access-date=2017-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170608202609/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-lang-jihae-join-peter-jacksons-mortal-engines-983628|archive-date=2017-06-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-lang-joins-jason-momoa-850022|title=Stephen Lang Joins Jason Momoa in Action Movie 'Braven' (Exclusive)|access-date=2016-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012072219/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-lang-joins-jason-momoa-850022|archive-date=2016-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/07/ben-foster-hostiles-scott-coopers-christian-bale-1201793493/|title=Ben Foster Rounds Out Scott Cooper's 'Hostiles' Cast As Shooting Starts|first=Mike Fleming|last=Jr|date=27 July 2016|access-date=2016-09-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905004722/http://deadline.com/2016/07/ben-foster-hostiles-scott-coopers-christian-bale-1201793493/|archive-date=2017-09-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Twice in a Lifetime (film)|Twice in a Lifetime]]'' \n| Keith\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Band of the Hand]]''\n| Joe\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Manhunter (film)|Manhunter]]''\n| [[Freddy Lounds]]\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Project X (1987 film)|Project X]]''\n| Watts\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Last Exit to Brooklyn (film)|Last Exit to Brooklyn]]''\n| Harry Black\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''{{sortname|The|Hard Way|dab=1991 film}}''\n| Party Crasher\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Another You]]''\n| Dibbs\n|\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Human Cargo]]''\n| Aramco Contractor\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Guilty as Sin]]''\n| Phil Garson\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]]''\n| Maj. Gen. [[George E. Pickett]]\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''The Making of Gettysburg'' \n| Himself/Maj. Gen. [[George E. Pickett]]\n| Video documentary\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Tombstone (film)|Tombstone]]''\n| [[Ike Clanton]]\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Tall Tale (film)|Tall Tale]]''\n| Jonas Hackett\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''{{sortname|The|Amazing Panda Adventure}}''\n| Dr. Michael Tyler\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Loose Women (film)|Loose Women]]''\n| Prophet Buddy \n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Gang in Blue]]''\n| Moose Tavola \n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''{{sortname|An|Occasional Hell}}''\n| Alex Laughton\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Shadow Conspiracy]]''\n| The Agent  \n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Niagara, Niagara]]''\n| Claude\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Fire Down Below (1997 film)|Fire Down Below]]''\n| Earl Kellogg \n|\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Story of a Bad Boy]]''\n| Spygo\n|\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Trixie (film)|Trixie]]''\n| Jacob Slotnick\n|-\n| 2001\n|''The Proposal''\n| Simon Bacig \n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[D-Tox]]''\n| Jack \n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''The Making of Tombstone''\n| Himself/[[Ike Clanton]]\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''{{sortname|The|I Inside}}''\n| Mr. Travitt\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Code 11-14''\n| Justin Shaw\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Gods and Generals (film)|Gods and Generals]]''\n| Gen. Thomas [[Stonewall Jackson|\"Stonewall\" Jackson]]\n| [[Movieguide]] Grace Award for Acting\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Gods and Generals: Journey to the Past''\n| Himself/Gen. Thomas [[Stonewall Jackson|\"Stonewall\" Jackson]]\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''{{sortname|The|Treatment|dab=2006 film}}''\n| Coach Galgano\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[We Fight to Be Free]]''\n| [[James Craik]]\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Save Me (2007 film)|Save Me]]''\n| Ted\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[From Mexico with Love]]''\n| Big Al Stevens\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Public Enemies (2009 film)|Public Enemies]]''\n| [[Charles B. Winstead|Charles Winstead]]\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''{{sortname|The|Men Who Stare at Goats|dab=film}}''\n| General Hopgood\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]''\n| Colonel Miles Quaritch\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actor]]<br/>Nominated \u2014 [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Villain]]<br/>Nominated \u2014 [[Teen Choice Award