{"title_page": "Richard Gant", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{For|the English actor, screenwriter and director|Richard E. Grant}}\n\n{{BLP IMDb refimprove|only=yes|date=July 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = \n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Richard Edward Gant\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1944|3|10}}\n| birth_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1980\u2013present\n| spouse = Arline Burks\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Richard Gant''' (born March 10, 1944) is an American actor. His credits include the films ''[[Rocky V]]'' (as the [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King]]-esque George Washington Duke), for which he received widespread critical acclaim.\n\n==Career==\nGant's other roles include a 1989 episode of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' as Battlin' Barry Gay, a possessed coroner in ''[[Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday]]'' (1993), ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'', ''[[The Big Lebowski]]'', ''[[Babylon 5]]'', ''[[Special Unit 2]]'', ''[[L.A. Law]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Living Single]]'', ''[[Posse (1993 film)|Posse]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Friends]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Men Don't Tell]]'', and ''[[Charmed]]''. He appeared in one episode of both ''[[Lois and Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'' and ''[[Smallville (TV series)|Smallville]]''. He also appeared in ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'' and ''[[Bean: The Ultimate Disaster Movie]]'' as well as reporter Charles Parker in the cult classic adaptation of Colin Bateman's ''[[Divorcing Jack (film)|Divorcing Jack]]''. He had a minor role as a senior naval officer in [[Roland Emmerich]]'s ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]''. Gant was also in the 2007 comedy film, ''[[Daddy Day Camp]]'', as Col. Buck Hinton.\n\nOn February 6, 2007, Gant joined the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] daytime drama ''[[General Hospital]]'' in the role of [[Russell Ford (GH)|Dr. Russell Ford]]. He starred in ''[[Men of a Certain Age]]'' for its entire two-season run on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] (2009\u20132011).\n\n==Other achievements==\nGant was the campaign manager for federal elections in the country of Nigeria. He has been honored for his achievements by being presented the Keys to the City of [[Oakland, California]] by then-Mayor [[Jerry Brown]]. Gant is also a member of [[Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n| ''Attica''\n| Eddie Lewis\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[Night of the Juggler]]''\n| Hospital Cop\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Death of a Prophet]]''\n| \n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Krush Groove]]''\n| Jay B\n| Credit as Richard E. Gant\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Suspect (1987 film)|Suspect]]''\n| Everett Bennett\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''Internal Affairs''\n| Police Commissioner\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Collision Course (1989 film)|Collision Course]]''\n| Jarryd Guard #2\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| ''Love or Money''\n| Zoo\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Freshman (1990 film)|The Freshman]]''\n| Lloyd Simpson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Rocky V]]''\n| George Washington Duke\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1991\n| ''[[Stone Cold (1991 film)|Stone Cold]]''\n| Cunningham\n|\n|-\n| ''False Arrest''\n| Detective John Volland\n|\n|-\n| ''Revenge of the Nerds''\n| P.T. Turner\n| Unaired TV pilot\n|-\n| ''Last Breeze of Summer''\n| Will Davis\n| Short\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Condition: Critical''\n| Sergeant Lidner\n| TV Movie\n|-\n|1993\n| ''The Tower''\n| Wilson\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Diagnosis Murder]]''\n| Det. Jim Michaels\n| TV Series\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[CB4]]''\n| Baa Baa Ack\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Men Don't Tell]]''\n| Pope\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Posse (1993 film)|Posse]]''\n| Doubletree\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n|''[[Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday]]''\n| Phil the Coroner\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''MacShayne: The Final Roll of the Dice''\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Trial by Fire''\n| Judge\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1996\n| ''[[City Hall (film)|City Hall]]''\n| Deputy Commissioner Samuels\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ed (film)|Ed]]''\n| Umpire, Sharks Game\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Glimmer Man]]''\n| Detective Roden\n|\n|-\n| ''Raven''\n| Russ Carlson\n| Direct-to-video release\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Bean (film)|Bean]]''\n| Lieutenant Brutus\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\"| 1998\n| ''[[The Big Lebowski]]''\n| Older Cop\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Sour Grapes (1998 film)|Sour Grapes]]''\n| Detective Crouch\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]''\n| Admiral Phelps\n| Credit as Richard E. Gant\n|-\n| ''[[Divorcing Jack (film)|Divorcing Jack]]''\n| Charles Parker\n| \n|-\n| ''Johnny B Good''\n| \n| Credit as Richard E. Gant\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]''\n| Mr. Gaines\n|\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Kingdom Come (2001 film)|Kingdom Come]]''\n| Clyde Kincade\n|\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[Smallville]]''\n| Principal Terrance Reynolds\n| TV Series\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''The Partners''\n| Deputy Chief\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Layla's Girl''\n| JB\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2006\n| ''[[Hood of Horror]]''\n| Jackson\n|\n|-\n| ''Summertime''\n| Paul Reeseman\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\"| 2007\n| ''Ezra''\n| Mac Mondale\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Norbit]]''\n| Preacher\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Fist of the Warrior]]''\n| Chief Matthews\n|\n|-\n| ''Young Ceaser''\n|\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Daddy Day Camp]]''\n| Colonel Buck Hinton\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Cover (film)|Cover]]''\n| Robert Mass\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2010\n| ''[[Waiting for Forever]]''\n| Albert\n|\n|-\n| ''Ashes''\n| Thomas Muller\n|\n|-\n| ''Screwball: The Ted Whitfield Story''\n| Paps \"Pure Plastic\" Patterson\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Mama & Me''\n| Himself\n| Documentary\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Island Song''\n| Duke\n| Short\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| ''[[Bleach (2014 film)|Bleach]]''\n| Harvey\n|\n|-\n| ''The Fright Night Files''\n| Michael\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Mr. Iglesias]]''\n| Ray Hayward\n| NETFLIX Original series\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0304579|name=Richard Gant}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gant, Richard}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Berkeley High School (Berkeley, California) alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n\n\n{{US-screen-actor-1940s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{For|the English actor, screenwriter and director|Richard E. Grant}}\n\n{{BLP IMDb refimprove|only=yes|date=July 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = \n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Richard Edward Gant\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1944|3|10}}\n| birth_place = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| occupation = Actor\n| years_active = 1980\u2013present\n| spouse = Arline Burks\n| children = 1\n}}\n'''Richard Gant''' (born March 10, 1944) is an American actor. His credits include the films ''[[Rocky V]]'' (as the [[Don King (boxing promoter)|Don King]]-esque George Washington Duke), for which he received widespread critical acclaim.\n\n==Career==\nGant's other roles include a 1989 episode of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' as Battlin' Barry Gay, a possessed coroner in ''[[Jason Goes to Hell: The Final Friday]]'' (1993), ''[[Deadwood (TV series)|Deadwood]]'', ''[[The Big Lebowski]]'', ''[[Babylon 5]]'', ''[[Special Unit 2]]'', ''[[L.A. Law]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[Living Single]]'', ''[[Posse (1993 film)|Posse]]'', ''[[Seinfeld]]'', ''[[Friends]]'', ''[[How I Met Your Mother]]'', ''[[Men Don't Tell]]'', and ''[[Charmed]]''. He appeared in one episode of both ''[[Lois and Clark: The New Adventures of Superman]]'' and ''[[Smallville (TV series)|Smallville]]''. He also appeared in ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'' and ''[[Bean: The Ultimate Disaster Movie]]'' as well as reporter Charles Parker in the cult classic adaptation of Colin Bateman's ''[[Divorcing Jack (film)|Divorcing Jack]]''. He had a minor role as a senior naval officer in [[Roland Emmerich]]'s ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]''. Gant was also in the 2007 comedy film, ''[[Daddy Day Camp]]'', as Col. Buck Hinton.\n\nOn February 6, 2007, Gant joined the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] daytime drama ''[[General Hospital]]'' in the role of [[Russell Ford (GH)|Dr. Russell Ford]]. He starred in ''[[Men of a Certain Age]]'' for its entire two-season run on [[TNT Network|TNT]] (2009\u20132011).\n\n==Other achievements==\nGant was the campaign manager for federal elections in the country of Nigeria. He has been honored for his achievements by being presented the Keys to the City of [[Oakland, California]] by then-Mayor [[Jerry Brown]]. Gant is also a member of [[Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1980\n| ''Attica''\n| Eddie Lewis\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[Night of the Juggler]]''\n| Hospital Cop\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Death of a Prophet]]''\n| \n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Krush Groove]]''\n| Jay B\n| Credit as Richard E. Gant\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Suspect (1987 film)|Suspect]]''\n| Everett Bennett\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''Internal Affairs''\n| Police Commissioner\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Collision Course (1989 film)|Collision Course]]''\n| Jarryd Guard #2\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1990\n| ''Love or Money''\n| Zoo\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Freshman (1990 film)|The Freshman]]''\n| Lloyd Simpson\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Rocky V]]''\n| George Washington Duke\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 1991\n| ''[[Stone Cold (1991 film)|Stone Cold]]''\n| Cunningham\n|\n|-\n| ''False Arrest''\n| Detective John Volland\n|\n|-\n| ''Revenge of the Nerds''\n| P.T. Turner\n| Unaired TV pilot\n|-\n| ''Last Breeze of Summer''\n| Will Davis\n| Short\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''Condition: Critical''\n