|FRA}}\n|style=background:#CEDFF2|'''{{sortname|Johann|Zarco}}'''\n|align=center|23\n|align=center|{{MGP|2009}}\u2013\n|[[2011 Italian motorcycle Grand Prix|2011 125cc Italian Grand Prix]]\n|[[2018 French motorcycle Grand Prix|2018 MotoGP French Grand Prix]]\n|}\n\n==By nationality==\n{{updated|21 October 2018}}\n{|class=\"sortable plainrowheaders wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=col|Rank\n!scope=col|Country\n!scope=col|Wins\n!scope=col|Rider(s)\n|-\n|align=center| 1\n!scope=row|{{ESP}}\n|align=center| 147\n|align=center| 2\n|-\n|align=center| 2\n!scope=row|{{ITA}}\n|align=center| 65\n|align=center| 1\n|}\n\n==References==\n;General\n* {{cite web|url=http://resources.motogp.com/files/results/xx/2015/VAL/table4.pdf |title=Riders All Time in All Classes |publisher=MotoGp |format=PDF |accessdate=8 November 2015}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/Results+Statistics/Statistics/statsearch |title=Statistics |publisher=MotoGP |accessdate=5 April 2011 }}\n\n;Specific\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{MotoGP}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Grand Prix motorcycle racers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{MotoGP overview}}\n[[File:Marc Marquez Aragon 2016.jpg|thumb|[[Marc M\u00e1rquez]], who holds the record with 90 Grands Prix pole positions during his career]]\n[[Grand Prix motorcycle racing]] is the premier championship of [[motorcycle]] [[road racing]], which has been divided into three classes since [[1990 Grand Prix motorcycle racing season|1990]]; 125cc, 250cc and MotoGP. Former classes that are now discontinued include 350cc, 50cc and [[sidecar]]s.<ref name=\"Guiness\">{{cite book|last=Marshall|first=Anne|title=Guinness Book of Knowledge|publisher=Guinness Publishing|year=1997|isbn=0-85112-046-6 |page=289}}</ref> The premier class is MotoGP, which was formerly known as the 500cc class.<ref name=\"Guiness\"/> The Grand Prix Road-Racing World Championship was established in 1949 by the sport's governing body the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme]] (FIM), and is the oldest motorsport World Championship in existence.<ref name=\"MotoGP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/About+MotoGP|title=About MotoGP|publisher=MotoGP|accessdate=24 December 2008}}</ref> The motorcycles used in MotoGP are purpose built for the sport, and are unavailable for purchase by the general public: they cannot be legally ridden on public roads.<ref name=\"MotoGP\"/>\n\n[[Marc M\u00e1rquez]] holds the record for the most Grand Prix pole positions, with 90. [[Jorge Lorenzo]] is second with 69 poles, and [[Valentino Rossi]] is third with 65 poles.\n\n==By rider==\n{{updated|19 October 2019}}\n{{Expand list|date=November 2018}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Key\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; width:47px; background:#FBCEB1;\"|\n|MotoGP / 500cc World Champion\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; width:47px; background:#CEDFF2;\"|\n|Grand Prix World Champion\n|-\n|'''Bold'''\n|Rider has competed in the {{MGP|2019}} season\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Grand Prix motorcycle racing polesitters\n!scope=col|Rank\n!scope=col|Country\n!scope=col|Rider\n!scope=col|Poles\n!scope=col|Seasons active\n!scope=col|First pole\n!scope=col|Last pole\n|-\n|align=center|1\n|{{flag|ESP}}\n|style=background:#FBCEB1|'''{{sortname|Marc|M\u00e1rquez}}'''\n|align=center|90\n|align=center|{{MGP|2008}}\u2013\n|[[2009 French motorcycle Grand Prix|2009 125cc French Grand Prix]]\n|[[2019 Japanese motorcycle Grand Prix|2019 MotoGP Japanese Grand Prix]]\n|-\n|align=center|2\n|{{flag|ESP}}\n|style=background:#FBCEB1|'''{{sortname|Jorge|Lorenzo}}'''\n|align=center|69\n|align=center|{{MGP|2002}}\u2013\n|[[2003 Malaysian motorcycle Grand Prix|2003 125cc Malaysian Grand Prix]]\n|[[2018 Aragon motorcycle Grand Prix|2018 MotoGP Aragon Grand Prix]]\n|-\n|align=center|3\n|{{flag|ITA}}\n|style=background:#FBCEB1|'''{{sortname|Valentino|Rossi}}'''\n|align=center|65\n|align=center|{{MGP|1996}}\u2013\n|[[1996 Czech Republic motorcycle Grand Prix|1996 125cc Czech 